# Software Requirements Specification (SRS)
## Project: NDIS Provider Management Mobile Application
## Location: Sydney, Australia

---

## 1. Introduction

### 1.1 Purpose
This document defines the functional and non-functional requirements for a mobile application designed to assist NDIS providers in Sydney with client management, scheduling, communication, and compliance reporting.

### 1.2 Scope
The application will provide an integrated platform for NDIS service providers to manage daily operations efficiently while ensuring compliance with NDIS regulations.

---

## 2. Overall Description

### 2.1 Product Perspective
The system is a mobile-first application that replaces fragmented tools (manual records, spreadsheets, and disconnected systems) with a unified solution.

### 2.2 Product Functions
- Client data management  
- Appointment scheduling  
- Staff-client communication  
- Compliance tracking and reporting  
- Notifications and reminders  

---

## 3. User Personas

### 3.1 Support Worker (Primary User)
- **Goals:** Deliver services efficiently, access client info quickly  
- **Needs:** Mobile access, real-time updates, easy reporting  
- **Pain Points:** Manual paperwork, scheduling conflicts  

### 3.2 Provider Administrator
- **Goals:** Manage staff, ensure compliance, oversee operations  
- **Needs:** Reporting tools, dashboards, data accuracy  
- **Pain Points:** Time-consuming compliance processes  

### 3.3 NDIS Participant (Secondary User)
- **Goals:** Receive timely services, communicate easily  
- **Needs:** Appointment visibility, communication channel  
- **Pain Points:** Lack of transparency and updates  

---

## 4. Functional Requirements

### 4.1 Client Management
- FR1: The system shall allow users to create, update, and delete client profiles  
- FR2: The system shall store NDIS-related participant information securely  
- FR3: The system shall allow quick search and retrieval of client records  

### 4.2 Appointment Scheduling
- FR4: The system shall allow booking, updating, and cancelling appointments  
- FR5: The system shall provide a calendar view for schedules  
- FR6: The system shall send reminders for upcoming appointments  

### 4.3 Communication
- FR7: The system shall support in-app messaging between staff and clients  
- FR8: The system shall send notifications for important updates  

### 4.4 Compliance & Reporting
- FR9: The system shall generate reports aligned with NDIS requirements  
- FR10: The system shall track service delivery against client plans  
- FR11: The system shall flag compliance issues  

### 4.5 User Authentication
- FR12: The system shall provide secure login/logout functionality  
- FR13: The system shall support role-based access control  

---

## 5. Non-Functional Requirements

### 5.1 Usability
- The app must be easy to use for non-technical users  
- The interface must be mobile-friendly and accessible  

### 5.2 Performance
- The system should load screens within 2 seconds  
- The system should handle multiple users simultaneously  

### 5.3 Security
- Data must be encrypted (at rest and in transit)  
- Must comply with Australian data privacy standards  

### 5.4 Reliability
- The system should have 99% uptime  
- Data loss must be prevented with backups  

### 5.5 Scalability
- The system must support growing numbers of users and clients  

---

## 6. User Stories

### 6.1 Support Worker
- As a support worker, I want to view my daily schedule so that I can manage my tasks efficiently  
- As a support worker, I want to update service notes after appointments so that records stay accurate  

### 6.2 Administrator
- As an admin, I want to generate compliance reports so that I meet NDIS requirements  
- As an admin, I want to manage staff schedules so that operations run smoothly  

### 6.3 Participant
- As a participant, I want to receive appointment reminders so that I don’t miss services  
- As a participant, I want to communicate with my support worker so that I can stay informed  

---

## 7. System Requirements

### 7.1 Platform
- Mobile application (iOS and Android)

### 7.2 Database
- Cloud-based secure database  

### 7.3 Integration
- Potential integration with NDIS systems and third-party tools  

---

## 8. Assumptions and Constraints

### Assumptions
- Users have access to smartphones  
- Internet connectivity is available  

### Constraints
- Must comply with NDIS regulations  
- Limited development timeframe (academic project)  

---

## 9. Success Criteria

- Reduced administrative workload  
- Improved scheduling efficiency  
- Increased compliance accuracy  
- Enhanced user satisfaction  

---

## 10. Conclusion

This SRS outlines the requirements for a mobile solution that addresses the operational challenges faced by NDIS providers in Sydney, aiming to improve efficiency, compliance, and service delivery.

